hands_on_practices.problem:
A homogeneous, isotropic, linear-elastic solid in the small-strain regime is characterized by Young’s modulus $E=200\,\mathrm{GPa}$ and Poisson’s ratio $\nu=0.3$. In a two-dimensional in-plane formulation using Voigt notation with the engineering shear strain, the constitutive relation is
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_{x} \\
\sigma_{y} \\
\tau_{xy}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\boldsymbol{D}
\begin{pmatrix}
\epsilon_{x} \\
\epsilon_{y} \\
\gamma_{xy}
\end{pmatrix},
$$
where $\gamma_{xy}=2\,\epsilon_{xy}$ and $\boldsymbol{D}$ is the reduced in-plane stiffness matrix. Compute the component $D_{11}$ of $\boldsymbol{D}$ for both plane stress and plane strain. Report the two values as a single row vector in the order $\bigl(D_{11}^{\text{(plane stress)}},\,D_{11}^{\text{(plane strain)}}\bigr)$. Express your final numbers in $\mathrm{GPa}$ and round your answers to four significant figures.
